{
    "body": [
        "Hi,\n\nI've been evaluating Salt today and I really like a lot that I've been seeing. I have two questions about the crypto design choices. A selling point of salt is speed but it appears that you are using some outdated algos here and I wanted to know why https://github.com/saltstack/salt/blob/9f24ec2d8d02fe75f32721e9e084be32dbece08c/salt/crypt.py\n\n1) RSA is used instead of ECC. There appears to be no outside dependencies requiring salt to use CPU intensive RSA instead of CPU light ECC. In the broader Internet, people blame the lack of traction on ECC keys on TLS due to lagging support from 3rd party apps like curl or ssh. I can't think of any requirement however on why that would be the case for salt which is just ZMQ between nodes. There are proven ECC curves like curve25519 with well thought out characteristics that include large performance gains in every benchmark I have seen. If you must include NIST approved curves for some reason, you could even use one of those.\n\n2) HMAC-SHA256. Although this choice of a MAC is better then say HMAC-SHA1 it is still exponentially slower and more expensive then AES-GCM. Since you already use AES for encryption already, this code appears to be redundant, you can run AES-GCM and get your encryption and authentication done in one function instead of two. AES-GCM has been around since 2007 and is no more bleeding edge then MQ or docker (http://csrc.nist.gov/publications/nistpubs/800-38D/SP-800-38D.pdf). \n\n3) A lack of crypto agility https://media.blackhat.com/bh-us-10/whitepapers/Sullivan/BlackHat-USA-2010-Sullivan-Cryptographic-Agility-wp.pdf \"One size fits all\" might work for Bitcoin but maybe that should not be the case for Salt. In the event of AES, SHA, or RSA getting cracked it would be advantageous for Salt customers to just add a command line option for swapping algos instead of having to manually update their software.\n\nThe only objection I could expect anyone to make about these suggests is that \"we tested this and we have not seen a performance gain to be worth it.\" Another one is \"changing this code is risky, we don't do that for mission critical functions\" but I doubt that is the case. Thanks for reading, hope it spurns some dev cycles towards it (if I was good enough at doing the above suggestions in python I would fork and try to do it myself).\n"
    ],
