{
    "body": [
        "Noticed this while randomly reading through the source code to `mtrand.c` (as generated from `mtrand.pyx`):

```
~$ python3
Python 3.4.2 (default, Oct  8 2014, 10:45:20) 
[GCC 4.9.1] on linux
Type "help", "copyright", "credits" or "license" for more information.
>>> import sys
>>> "mtrand" in sys.modules
False
>>> import numpy
>>> "mtrand" in sys.modules
True
>>> import mtrand
>>> mtrand
<module 'numpy.random.mtrand' from '/usr/lib/python3/dist-packages/numpy/random/mtrand.cpython-34m-x86_64-linux-gnu.so'>
>>> numpy.random.mtrand
<module 'numpy.random.mtrand' from '/usr/lib/python3/dist-packages/numpy/random/mtrand.cpython-34m-x86_64-linux-gnu.so'>
>>> sys.modules["numpy.random.mtrand"]
<module 'numpy.random.mtrand' from '/usr/lib/python3/dist-packages/numpy/random/mtrand.cpython-34m-x86_64-linux-gnu.so'>
```

The problem is the following code inside the Cython-generated module init function:

```
  #if PY_MAJOR_VERSION >= 3
  {
    PyObject *modules = PyImport_GetModuleDict(); if (unlikely(!modules)) {__pyx_filename = __pyx_f[0]; __pyx_lineno = 1; __pyx_clineno = __LINE__; goto __pyx_L1_error;}
    if (!PyDict_GetItemString(modules, "mtrand")) {
      if (unlikely(PyDict_SetItemString(modules, "mtrand", __pyx_m) < 0)) {__pyx_filename = __pyx_f[0]; __pyx_lineno = 1; __pyx_clineno = __LINE__; goto __pyx_L1_error;}
    }
  }
  #endif
```

which is just... "if this is python 3, then do `sys.modules["mtrand"] = this module`".

I don't know why Cython does this. If you look at the above REPL trace, it's clear that the `mtrand` module does end up with a properly qualified `__name__`, and does end up in the proper fully-qualified place in `sys.modules` as well, so... maybe this is just a bug in Cython, and the C code I quoted above should just not be generated?
"
    ],
    "title": [
        "On Py3, import numpy adds an "mtrand" package to sys.modules"
    ],
